{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657606"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20579"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20579"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.17,0.04,0,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93727"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20579"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12502"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93727"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAneurysms are focal dilatations of arteries that can occur as a consequence of various pathological processes. Atherosclerosis is a common underlying cause of aneurysm formation in certain arterial segments.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arterial sites is most commonly affected by atherosclerotic aneurysms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infra-renal abdominal aorta","Thoracic aorta above the diaphragm","Cerebral arteries of the Circle of Willis","Popliteal arteries behind the knee","Coronary arteries of the heart"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal aorta below the renal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common site for atherosclerotic aneurysm formation. These infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs) account for approximately 75% of all aortic aneurysms. The common iliac arteries are the second most frequent location. The predilection for this site is related to hemodynamic factors, including turbulent blood flow and wall stress, combined with the relative paucity of vasa vasorum in this region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracic aorta above the diaphragm \u003C/strong\u003Eis less commonly affected by atherosclerotic aneurysms. Aneurysms in this location are more frequently associated with other etiologies such as genetic disorders (e.g., Marfan syndrome), cystic medial degeneration, or trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral arteries of the Circle of Willis \u003C/strong\u003Etypically develop saccular (berry) aneurysms rather than atherosclerotic aneurysms. These cerebral aneurysms are primarily related to congenital weaknesses in the arterial wall and hemodynamic stress at arterial bifurcations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epopliteal arteries behind the knee \u003C/strong\u003Ecan develop atherosclerotic aneurysms, but they are much less common than abdominal aortic aneurysms. Popliteal aneurysms represent the second most common peripheral arterial aneurysm after femoral aneurysms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoronary arteries of the heart \u003C/strong\u003Erarely develop true aneurysms. When coronary aneurysms do occur, they are more commonly associated with inflammatory conditions like Kawasaki disease or complications of percutaneous coronary interventions rather than atherosclerosis alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for atherosclerotic aneurysms include smoking, hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, male sex, and advanced age. The pathogenesis involves degradation of elastin and collagen in the arterial wall, inflammatory processes, and biomechanical wall stress.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atherosclerotic aneurysms most commonly form in the abdominal aorta below the renal arteries.","Aneurysms are defined as focal dilatations of an artery with at least a 50% increase in diameter compared to normal.","Risk factors for atherosclerotic aneurysms include smoking, hypertension, male sex, and advanced age."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 506"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20579"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:19:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T09:19:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13456"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93727"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"hea